# `template.tsx` — intentional remount/reset boundary

## Doctrine

```txt
template.tsx = intentional remount / reset boundary
```

`template.tsx` is similar to `layout.tsx` in that it wraps children — but unlike layouts, templates receive a **unique key on navigation**, causing children Client Components to reset their state and effects to re-synchronize.

Docs: [Next.js — template.js](https://nextjs.org/docs/app/api-reference/file-conventions/template)

---

## Afenda rule

```md
Do not introduce template.tsx unless the desired behaviour is to intentionally
remount Client Components at that exact segment boundary.

Defer unless the reset requirement is explicit and proven.
```

This is not a layout alternative. It is a **reset weapon** — powerful when you need it, harmful when added without intent.

---

## What template does (docs-validated)

On navigation:

- Templates receive a **unique key for their own segment level**
- Child Client Components **reset all state**
- `useEffect` hooks **re-synchronize** (fire cleanup + setup again)
- DOM elements inside the template are **fully recreated**

On searches and inner-segment navigation:

- **Search params do NOT trigger remounts**
- **Inner-segment navigations do NOT remount a higher-level template**
  — navigating from `dashboard/contacts` to `dashboard/sale` does NOT remount a `dashboard/template.tsx`

Segment level remount only:
```
/o/acme/dashboard → /o/beta/dashboard  — remounts dashboard/template.tsx ✓
/o/acme/dashboard/contacts → /o/acme/dashboard/sale  — does NOT remount dashboard/template.tsx ✗
```

For per-module state reset, add `template.tsx` inside that module's own segment.

---

## Component hierarchy

```
layout → template → error → [loading wraps] → not-found / page
```

`template.tsx` sits between `layout.tsx` and the error/loading/page layer. The layout persists; the template remounts.

---

## Correct use cases

Add `template.tsx` **only** when you need to reset:

```txt
local client state when the segment's params change
useEffect to re-fire on every navigation within this segment
inspector / command scope state tied to the current route
form island state that must clear on segment change
animation lifecycle that should restart on each navigation
Suspense boundaries that must show the fallback on every navigation (not just first load)
```

The last point is important: **Suspense inside `layout.tsx` only shows its fallback on first load**. Suspense inside `template.tsx` shows the fallback on every navigation to that segment.

---

## Do NOT use `template.tsx` for

```txt
normal shell positioning or visual layout
breadcrumb or navigation updates
page-level data refresh (use Server Action revalidation instead)
module navigation (inner-segment navigation does not trigger remount)
general layout composition
```

---

## When you might actually need it in Afenda

| Scenario | File location | Reason |
| -------- | ------------- | ------ |
| Inspector state must reset when navigating between contacts | `dashboard/contacts/[id]/template.tsx` | Reset detail-panel client state on record change |
| Command palette scope must clear on module switch | `dashboard/[module]/template.tsx` | Each module gets fresh command scope |
| Form island must clear when navigating to a different segment | Segment-level `template.tsx` | Forces form island unmount |
| Suspense fallback must show on every module navigation | `dashboard/template.tsx` | Layout Suspense only shows once |

---

## Minimal template pattern

```tsx
// dashboard/contacts/[id]/template.tsx
export default function ContactDetailTemplate({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return <>{children}</>
}
```

The template adds no markup — its only effect is the unique key that causes remount. Keep it transparent.

---

## Anti-pattern — template as a layout substitute

```tsx
// WRONG — using template for visual layout
export default function Template({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <div className="grid grid-cols-[sidebar] gap-6">
      <Sidebar />
      {children}
    </div>
  )
}
```

This rebuilds the sidebar on every navigation. Use `layout.tsx` instead.

---

## Relationship to `layout.tsx`

`layout.tsx` **persists** across navigations within its segment — state is maintained, effects are not re-fired.

`template.tsx` **remounts** on navigation to its segment — state resets, effects re-fire.

Use `layout.tsx` for persistent shell authority. Add `template.tsx` only when you need the opposite.

See `layout-contract.mdc` for the full runtime kernel doctrine.
